{\an8} [English] ♫ ...glory. ♫

56
00:03:40,809 --> 00:03:42,609
It was in this moment...

57
00:03:42,909 --> 00:03:45,209
... when all hope had faded...

58
00:03:45,509 --> 00:03:49,409
... that Isildur, son of the king,
took up his father's sword.

59
00:04:20,710 --> 00:04:26,910
Sauron, the enemy of the free peoples
of Middle-earth, was defeated.

60
00:04:34,111 --> 00:04:36,211
The ring passed to Isildur...

61
00:04:36,511 --> 00:04:40,511
... who had this one chance to destroy evil forever.

62
00:04:41,411 --> 00:04:43,411
But the hearts of men...

63
00:04:43,711 --> 00:04:46,111
...are easily corrupted.

64
00:04:46,511 --> 00:04:50,911
And the ring of power has a will of its own.

65
00:05:16,312 --> 00:05:18,812
It betrayed Isildur...

66
00:05:20,813 --> 00:05:23,113
... to his death.

67
00:05:27,413 --> 00:05:31,113
And some things
that should not have been forgotten...

68
00:05:31,413 --> 00:05:33,613
...were lost.

69
00:05:34,513 --> 00:05:36,713
History became legend...

70
00:05:37,013 --> 00:05:38,913
...legend became myth.

71
00:05:39,213 --> 00:05:41,913
And for two and a half thousand years...

72
00:05:42,313 --> 00:05:45,913
... the ring passed out of all knowledge.

73
00:05:46,614 --> 00:05:49,314
Until, when chance came...

74
00:05:50,114 --> 00:05:53,114
...it ensnared a new bearer.

75
00:05:54,614 --> 00:05:59,214
My precious.

76
00:05:59,714 --> 00:06:02,114
The ring came to the creature Gollum...

77
00:06:02,414 --> 00:06:06,114
... who took it deep into the tunnels
of the Misty Mountains.

78
00:06:06,614 --> 00:06:09,414
And there it consumed him.

79
00:06:09,714 --> 00:06:11,614
It came to me.

80
00:06:11,915 --> 00:06:16,215
My own. My love. My own.

81
00:06:16,615 --> 00:06:21,115
My precious.

82
00:06:24,915 --> 00:06:28,215
The ring brought to Gollum unnatural long life.

83
00:06:28,615 --> 00:06:32,215
For 500 years it poisoned his mind.

84
00:06:32,515 --> 00:06:36,915
And in the gloom of Gollum's cave, it waited.

85
00:06:37,315 --> 00:06:40,516
Darkness crept back into the forests of the world.

86
00:06:40,916 --> 00:06:43,616
Rumor grew of a shadow in the East...

87
00:06:43,916 --> 00:06:46,616
... whispers of a nameless fear.

88
00:06:46,916 --> 00:06:50,116
And the ring of power perceived...

89
00:06:50,516 --> 00:06:53,116
...its time had now come.

90
00:06:55,716 --> 00:06:58,216
It abandoned Gollum.

91
00:06:59,016 --> 00:07:03,217
But something happened then
the ring did not intend.

92
00:07:04,317 --> 00:07:08,717
It was picked up by the most
unlikely creature imaginable.

93
00:07:09,117 --> 00:07:10,117
What's this?

94
00:07:10,417 --> 00:07:11,816
A hobbit.

95
00:07:11,817 --> 00:07:14,617
Bilbo Baggins of the Shire.

96
00:07:15,017 --> 00:07:16,716
A ring.

97
00:07:16,717 --> 00:07:18,717
Lost!

98
00:07:20,217 --> 00:07:23,116
The 22nd day of September...

99
00:07:23,117 --> 00:07:24,817
My precious is lost!

100
00:07:25,217 --> 00:07:27,417
For the time will soon come...

101
00:07:27,817 --> 00:07:32,718
... when Hobbits will shape the fortunes of all.

102
00:07:40,918 --> 00:07:44,018
...in the year 1400...

103
00:07:44,418 --> 00:07:46,617
...by Shire-reckoning.

104
00:07:46,618 --> 00:07:52,418
Bag End, Bagshot Row.
Hobbiton, Westfarthing...

105
00:07:52,818 --> 00:07:54,719
...the Shire...

106
00:07:55,019 --> 00:07:57,719
...Middle-earth.

107
00:08:02,419 --> 00:08:05,619
The third age of this world.

108
00:08:08,019 --> 00:08:13,019
The Fellowship of the Ring.

109
00:08:17,419 --> 00:08:19,919
There and back again.

110
00:08:21,920 --> 00:08:23,620
A Hobbit's tale.

111
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:27,720
By Bilbo Baggins.

112
00:08:32,620 --> 00:08:34,220
Now...

113
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:37,020
...where to begin?

114
00:08:38,420 --> 00:08:39,420
Ah, yes....

115
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:45,721
"Concerning...

116
00:08:46,921 --> 00:08:48,421
...Hobbits."

117
00:08:49,621 --> 00:08:53,021
Hobbits have been living and farming
in the four Farthings of the Shire...

118
00:08:53,321 --> 00:08:55,320
...for many hundreds of years...

119
00:08:55,321 --> 00:08:58,620
...quite content to ignore and be ignored...

120
00:08:58,621 --> 00:09:01,721
...by the world of the big folk.

121
00:09:02,221 --> 00:09:07,621
Middle-earth being, after all,
full of strange creatures beyond count...

122
00:09:08,021 --> 00:09:11,121
...Hobbits must seem of little importance...

123
00:09:11,422 --> 00:09:15,222
...being neither renowned as great warriors...

124
00:09:15,622 --> 00:09:19,622
...nor counted among the very wise.

125
00:09:24,122 --> 00:09:27,022
Frodo! Someone at the door.

126
00:09:28,322 --> 00:09:30,822
In fact, it has been remarked by some...

127
00:09:31,122 --> 00:09:35,322
... that Hobbits' only real passion is for food.

128
00:09:35,922 --> 00:09:38,023
A rather unfair observation...

129
00:09:38,323 --> 00:09:41,723
...as we have also developed a keen
interest in the brewing of ales...

130
00:09:42,423 --> 00:09:45,023
...and the smoking of pipe-weed.

131
00:09:45,623 --> 00:09:48,323
But where our hearts truly lie...

132
00:09:48,623 --> 00:09:50,623
...is in peace and quiet...

133
00:09:51,523 --> 00:09:53,523
...and good, tilled earth.

134
00:09:53,823 --> 00:09:58,823
For all Hobbits share a love of things that grow.

135
00:10:02,123 --> 00:10:06,324
And yes, no doubt to others our ways seem quaint.

136
00:10:06,724 --> 00:10:11,724
But today of all days.
It is brought home to me...

137
00:10:12,524 --> 00:10:18,224
It is no bad thing to celebrate a simple life.

138
00:10:22,624 --> 00:10:25,724
Frodo, the door!

139
00:10:29,625 --> 00:10:31,524
Sticklebacks. Where is that boy?

140
00:10:31,525 --> 00:10:33,425
Frodo!

141
00:10:39,225 --> 00:10:42,625
<i>Down from the door where it began</i>

142
00:10:47,625 --> 00:10:51,225
<i>And I must follow if I can</i>

143
00:10:52,425 --> 00:10:56,426
<i>The road goes ever on and on</i>

144
00:10:56,726 --> 00:10:59,926
<i>Down from the door where it began</i>

145
00:11:00,426 --> 00:11:05,126
<i>Now far ahead the road has gone</i>

146
00:11:06,026 --> 00:11:09,626
<i>And I must follow if I can
- You're late.</i>

147
00:11:13,026 --> 00:11:16,726
A wizard is never late, Frodo Baggins.

148
00:11:17,626 --> 00:11:22,127
Nor is he early.
He arrives precisely when he means to.

149
00:11:33,627 --> 00:11:36,527
It's wonderful to see you, Gandalf!

150
00:11:40,527 --> 00:11:44,127
You didn't think I'd miss
your Uncle Bilbo's birthday?

151
00:11:45,928 --> 00:11:48,028
How is the old rascal?

152
00:11:48,728 --> 00:11:52,128
I hear it's going to be a party
of special magnificence.

153
00:11:52,428 --> 00:11:54,728
You know Bilbo.
He's got the whole piece in an uproar.

154
00:11:55,028 --> 00:11:56,927
Well, that should please him.

155
00:11:56,928 --> 00:11:58,928
Half the Shire's been invited.

156
00:11:59,328 --> 00:12:01,828
And the rest of them are turning up anyway.

157
00:12:05,028 --> 00:12:08,228
And so life in the Shire goes on...

158
00:12:08,628 --> 00:12:11,529
... very much as it has this past age.

159
00:12:11,829 --> 00:12:17,129
Full of its own comings and goings,
with change coming slowly.

160
00:12:17,429 --> 00:12:19,329
If it comes at all.

161
00:12:20,729 --> 00:12:24,029
For things are made to endure in the Shire...

162
00:12:24,329 --> 00:12:27,629
...passing from one generation to the next.

163
00:12:28,229 --> 00:12:33,029
There's always been a Baggins
living here under the Hill...

164
00:12:33,429 --> 00:12:34,729
...in Bag End.

165
00:12:37,530 --> 00:12:40,230
And there always will be.

166
00:12:41,030 --> 00:12:44,230
To tell you the truth,
Bilbo's been a bit odd lateIy.

167
00:12:45,630 --> 00:12:47,830
I mean, more than usual.

168
00:12:48,930 --> 00:12:50,730
He's taken to locking himself in his study.

169
00:12:52,430 --> 00:12:56,430
He spends hours and hours poring over
old maps when he thinks I'm not looking.

170
00:13:09,331 --> 00:13:10,931
Where's it gone?

171
00:13:37,532 --> 00:13:39,732
He's up to something.

172
00:13:47,932 --> 00:13:50,332
- All right, then. Keep your secrets.
- What?

173
00:13:50,632 --> 00:13:52,232
But I know you have something to do with it.

174
00:13:52,632 --> 00:13:53,633
Good gracious me.

175
00:13:54,133 --> 00:13:56,733
Before you came along, we Bagginses
were very well thought of.

176
00:13:57,133 --> 00:13:57,933
Indeed.

177
00:13:58,333 --> 00:14:00,433
Never had any adventures
or did anything unexpected.

178
00:14:01,133 --> 00:14:06,733
If you're referring to the incident with the dragon.
I was barely involved.

179
00:14:07,133 --> 00:14:10,633
All I did was give your uncle
a little nudge out of the door.

180
00:14:10,933 --> 00:14:14,933
Whatever you did, you've been officially
labeled a disturber of the peace.

181
00:14:15,533 --> 00:14:17,333
Oh, really?

182
00:14:23,034 --> 00:14:24,934
Gandalf! Gandalf!

183
00:14:31,134 --> 00:14:32,334
Fireworks, Gandalf!

184
00:14:35,434 --> 00:14:37,934
- Gandalf!
- Fireworks, Gandalf!

185
00:14:56,935 --> 00:14:57,935
Gandalf?

186
00:14:58,535 --> 00:15:02,435
- I'm glad you're back.
- So am I, dear boy.

187
00:15:07,035 --> 00:15:08,835
So am I.

188
00:15:40,737 --> 00:15:42,136
No, thank you!

189
00:15:42,137 --> 00:15:46,037
We don't want any more visitors,
well-wishers or distant relations!

190
00:15:46,537 --> 00:15:49,837
And what about very old friends?

191
00:15:53,237 --> 00:15:54,837
Gandalf?

192
00:15:55,537 --> 00:15:58,837
- Bilbo Baggins.
- My dear Gandalf!

193
00:15:59,237 --> 00:16:04,138
Good to see you. 111 years old!
Who would believe it?

194
00:16:06,138 --> 00:16:08,038
You haven't aged a day.

195
00:16:14,738 --> 00:16:16,638
Come on, come in!

196
00:16:16,938 --> 00:16:19,238
Welcome, welcome.

197
00:16:20,538 --> 00:16:22,938
Oh, here we are.

198
00:16:24,738 --> 00:16:27,137
Tea...or maybe something a littIe stronger?

199
00:16:27,138 --> 00:16:31,039
I've got a few bottles of the old winyard left - 1296.

200
00:16:31,339 --> 00:16:35,139
Very good year. Almost as old as I am.

201
00:16:36,539 --> 00:16:40,839
It was laid down by my father.
What say we open one, eh?

202
00:16:41,239 --> 00:16:43,739
Just tea, thank you.

203
00:16:50,339 --> 00:16:51,839
I was expecting you sometime last week.

204
00:16:52,139 --> 00:16:55,340
Not that it matters. You come and go as
you please. Always have and always will.

205
00:16:55,640 --> 00:17:00,640
You caught me a bit unprepared I'm afraid.
We've only got cold chicken and a bit of pickle....

206
00:17:01,040 --> 00:17:04,240
There's some cheese here.
No, that won't do.

207
00:17:04,640 --> 00:17:08,440
We've got raspberry jam, an apple tart....

208
00:17:09,240 --> 00:17:13,140
But not much for afters.
Oh, no, we're all right.

209
00:17:13,440 --> 00:17:16,140
I've just found some sponge cake.

210
00:17:19,241 --> 00:17:20,441
I could make you some eggs if you'd li...

211
00:17:24,341 --> 00:17:26,941
- Just tea, thank you.
- Oh, right.

212
00:17:28,041 --> 00:17:30,241
- You don't mind if I eat, do you?
- No, not at all.

213
00:17:31,541 --> 00:17:33,341
Bilbo! Bilbo Baggins!

214
00:17:33,641 --> 00:17:35,141
I'm not at home!

215
00:17:41,241 --> 00:17:43,741
It's the Sackville-Bagginses.

216
00:17:44,041 --> 00:17:46,042
- I know you're in there!
- They're after the house.

217
00:17:46,742 --> 00:17:49,142
They've never forgiven me for living this long.

218
00:17:49,442 --> 00:17:52,141
I've got to get away from these confounded
relatives, hanging on the bell all day...

219
00:17:52,142 --> 00:17:54,242
...never giving me a moment's peace.

220
00:17:55,142 --> 00:17:58,542
I want to see mountains again.
Mountains, Gandalf!

221
00:17:58,842 --> 00:18:03,242
And then find somewhere quiet
where I can finish my book. Oh, tea.

222
00:18:03,542 --> 00:18:07,342
- So you mean to go through with your plan?
- Yes, yes. It's all in hand.

223
00:18:07,742 --> 00:18:09,843
All the arrangements are made.

224
00:18:12,043 --> 00:18:13,443
Oh, thank you.

225
00:18:14,243 --> 00:18:16,243
Frodo suspects something.

226
00:18:16,543 --> 00:18:18,943
Of course he does. He's a Baggins...

227
00:18:19,243 --> 00:18:21,743
...not some blockheaded Bracegirdle
from Hardbottle.

228
00:18:22,443 --> 00:18:25,143
You will tell him, won't you?

229
00:18:26,043 --> 00:18:28,043
- Yes, yes.
- He's very fond of you.

230
00:18:30,343 --> 00:18:31,843
I know.

231
00:18:34,243 --> 00:18:37,544
He'd probably come with me if I asked him.

232
00:18:38,244 --> 00:18:41,444
I think in his heart, Frodo's
still in love with the Shire.

233
00:18:43,144 --> 00:18:45,444
The woods, the fields.

234
00:18:45,744 --> 00:18:47,944
Little rivers.

235
00:18:52,544 --> 00:18:55,144
I am old, Gandalf.

236
00:18:56,644 --> 00:19:01,645
I know I don't look it, but I'm
beginning to feel it in my heart.

237
00:19:04,045 --> 00:19:06,544
I feel thin.

238
00:19:06,545 --> 00:19:08,445
Sort of stretched...

239
00:19:09,745 --> 00:19:12,945
...like butter scraped over too much bread.

240
00:19:13,345 --> 00:19:17,645
I need a holiday. A very Long holiday.

241
00:19:17,945 --> 00:19:21,045
And I don't expect I shall return.

242
00:19:23,445 --> 00:19:26,545
In fact, I mean not to.

243
00:19:29,246 --> 00:19:33,146
Old Toby.
The finest weed in the Southfarthing.

244
00:19:50,746 --> 00:19:53,246
Gandalf, my old friend...

245
00:19:53,247 --> 00:19:56,147
...this will be a night to remember.

246
00:20:19,048 --> 00:20:20,148
Hello, hello.

247
00:20:20,448 --> 00:20:24,348
Fatty Bolger. Lovely to see you.
Welcome, welcome.

248
00:20:25,548 --> 00:20:27,948
Go on, Sam. Ask Rosie for a dance.

249
00:20:30,648 --> 00:20:34,048
- I think I'll just have another ale.
- Oh, no, you don't.

250
00:20:35,248 --> 00:20:37,048
Go on!

251
00:20:47,249 --> 00:20:48,949
So there I was...

252
00:20:49,249 --> 00:20:53,249
...at the mercy of three monstrous trolls.

253
00:20:53,549 --> 00:20:55,448
And they were all arguing amongst themselves...

254
00:20:55,449 --> 00:20:57,949
...about how they were going to cook us.

255
00:20:58,249 --> 00:21:03,149
Whether it be turned on a spit, or to sit
on us one by one, squash us into jelly.

256
00:21:04,349 --> 00:21:07,749
They spent so much time arguing
the whithertos and the whyfors...

257
00:21:08,049 --> 00:21:11,550
...that the sun's first light
crept over the top of the trees...

258
00:21:12,650 --> 00:21:15,050
...and turned them all to stone!

259
00:21:20,550 --> 00:21:21,850
Quickly.

260
00:21:26,050 --> 00:21:28,050
Up they go!

261
00:21:30,950 --> 00:21:32,250
No no, the big one - big one

262
00:21:41,351 --> 00:21:44,150
Mrs. Bracegirdle, how nice to see you.
Welcome, welcome.

263
00:21:44,151 --> 00:21:46,250
Are all these children yours?

264
00:21:46,251 --> 00:21:49,351
Good gracious, you have been productive.

265
00:21:51,451 --> 00:21:52,751
Bilbo?

266
00:21:54,451 --> 00:21:56,151
Sackville-Bagginses!

267
00:21:56,451 --> 00:21:57,451
Quickly, hide!

268
00:22:07,452 --> 00:22:09,552
Thank you, my boy.

269
00:22:11,152 --> 00:22:13,352
You're a good lad, Frodo.

270
00:22:14,752 --> 00:22:17,452
I'm very selfish, you know.

271
00:22:17,952 --> 00:22:21,352
Yes, I am. Very selfish.

272
00:22:21,852 --> 00:22:23,952
I don't know why I took you in after
your mother and father died...

273
00:22:24,252 --> 00:22:25,652
...but it wasn't out of charity.

274
00:22:26,353 --> 00:22:27,652
I think it was because...

275
00:22:27,653 --> 00:22:30,053
...of all my numerous relations...

276
00:22:30,453 --> 00:22:33,853
...you were the one Baggins that showed real spirit.

277
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:36,053
Bilbo, have you been at the Gaffer's home brew?

278
00:22:36,353 --> 00:22:37,953
No.

279
00:22:38,253 --> 00:22:40,753
Well, yes, but that's not the point.

280
00:22:41,153 --> 00:22:44,253
The point is, Frodo...

281
00:22:47,453 --> 00:22:49,353
...you'll be all right.

282
00:22:52,854 --> 00:22:54,754
- Done!
- You're supposed to stick it in the ground.

283
00:22:55,054 --> 00:22:56,553
- It is in the ground.
- Outside!

284
00:22:56,554 --> 00:22:58,254
This was your idea.

285
00:23:14,154 --> 00:23:15,654
Bilbo.

286
00:23:16,854 --> 00:23:19,455
Bilbo, watch out for the dragon!

287
00:23:19,755 --> 00:23:23,055
Nonsense. There hasn't been a dragon
in these parts for thousands of years.

288
00:23:36,655 --> 00:23:40,055
- That was good.
- Let's get another one.

289
00:23:41,555 --> 00:23:45,856
Meriadoc Brandybuck and Peregrin Took.

290
00:23:46,256 --> 00:23:48,056
I might've known.

291
00:23:54,056 --> 00:23:56,056
Speech, Bilbo!

292
00:23:57,056 --> 00:23:58,355
Speech!

293
00:23:58,356 --> 00:23:59,556
Speech!

294
00:24:04,856 --> 00:24:07,056
My dear Bagginses and Boffins...

295
00:24:07,856 --> 00:24:09,957
...Tooks and Brandybucks...

296
00:24:10,257 --> 00:24:12,657
...Grubbs, Chubbs...

297
00:24:12,957 --> 00:24:13,957
...Hornblowers...

298
00:24:15,157 --> 00:24:16,757
...Bolgers...

299
00:24:17,257 --> 00:24:18,757
...Bracegirdles...

300
00:24:19,057 --> 00:24:21,557
...and Proudfoots.
- Proudfeet!

301
00:24:23,857 --> 00:24:26,857
Today is my 111th birthday!

302
00:24:28,757 --> 00:24:30,256
Happy birthday!

303
00:24:30,257 --> 00:24:34,558
But alas, eleventh-one years is
far too short a time to live among...

304
00:24:34,958 --> 00:24:37,758
...such excellent and admirable Hobbits.

305
00:24:38,858 --> 00:24:41,458
I don't know half of you
half as well as I should like...

306
00:24:41,758 --> 00:24:46,158
...and I like less than half of you
half as well as you deserve.

307
00:24:56,358 --> 00:24:58,558
I have things to do.

308
00:25:05,059 --> 00:25:07,059
I've put this off for far too long.

309
00:25:11,059 --> 00:25:14,859
I regret to announce this is the end!

310
00:25:16,159 --> 00:25:17,259
I'm going now.

311
00:25:18,459 --> 00:25:21,259
I bid you all a very fond farewell.

312
00:25:23,659 --> 00:25:24,859
Goodbye.

313
00:25:58,161 --> 00:26:01,161
I suppose you think that was terribly clever.

314
00:26:01,561 --> 00:26:04,761
Come on, Gandalf.
Did you see their faces?

315
00:26:05,061 --> 00:26:07,860
There are many magic rings in
this world, Bilbo Baggins...

316
00:26:07,861 --> 00:26:10,160
...and none of them should be used lightly.

317
00:26:10,161 --> 00:26:12,361
It was just a bit of fun.

318
00:26:12,661 --> 00:26:16,261
Oh, you're probably right, as usual.

319
00:26:17,762 --> 00:26:21,162
- You will keep an eye on Frodo, won't you?
- Two eyes.

320
00:26:21,562 --> 00:26:24,062
As often as I can spare them.

321
00:26:24,362 --> 00:26:27,462
- I'm leaving everything to him.
- What about this ring of yours?

322
00:26:27,762 --> 00:26:30,962
- Is that staying too?
- Yes, yes.

323
00:26:31,762 --> 00:26:35,462
It's in an envelope over there on the mantelpiece.

324
00:26:36,662 --> 00:26:39,562
No. Wait, it's...

325
00:26:42,162 --> 00:26:44,763
...here in my pocket.

326
00:26:49,363 --> 00:26:52,563
Isn't that--? Isn't that odd, now?

327
00:26:54,363 --> 00:26:57,763
Yet, after all, why not?

328
00:26:59,363 --> 00:27:04,063
- Why shouldn t I keep it?
- I think you should leave the ring behind.

329
00:27:04,663 --> 00:27:06,763
Is that so hard?

330
00:27:07,063 --> 00:27:08,364
Well, no.

331
00:27:10,864 --> 00:27:12,264
And yes.

332
00:27:14,264 --> 00:27:17,264
Now it comes to it,
I don't feel l ike parting with it.

333
00:27:17,664 --> 00:27:19,364
It's mine. I found it! It came to me!

334
00:27:19,664 --> 00:27:23,664
- There's no need to get angry.
- Well, if I'm angry, it's your fault!

335
00:27:24,164 --> 00:27:25,864
It's mine.

336
00:27:27,364 --> 00:27:29,764
My own.

337
00:27:30,164 --> 00:27:33,965
- My precious.
- Precious?

338
00:27:34,365 --> 00:27:37,065
It's been called that before, but not by you.

339
00:27:37,465 --> 00:27:39,865
What business is it of yours
what I do with my own things?

340
00:27:40,165 --> 00:27:42,865
I think you've had that ring quite long enough.

341
00:27:43,165 --> 00:27:45,865
- You want it for yourself!
- Bilbo Baggins!

342
00:27:46,165 --> 00:27:50,265
Do not take me for some conjurer of cheap tricks.

343
00:27:50,665 --> 00:27:54,165
I am not trying to rob you.

344
00:27:59,365 --> 00:28:00,966
I'm trying to help you.

345
00:28:09,466 --> 00:28:12,666
All your long years, we've been friends.

346
00:28:13,166 --> 00:28:15,266
Trust me as you once did.

347
00:28:17,266 --> 00:28:18,966
Let it go.

348
00:28:20,166 --> 00:28:22,466
You're right, Gandalf.

349
00:28:24,666 --> 00:28:27,267
The ring must go to Frodo.

350
00:28:28,767 --> 00:28:31,667
It's late. The road is long.

351
00:28:31,967 --> 00:28:34,367
Yes, it is time.

352
00:28:37,167 --> 00:28:41,967
Bilbo, the ring is still in your pocket.

353
00:29:16,969 --> 00:29:19,869
I've thought up an ending for my book:

354
00:29:21,569 --> 00:29:26,369
"And he lived happily ever after
to the end of his days."

355
00:29:26,869 --> 00:29:30,169
And I'm sure you will, my dear friend.

356
00:29:31,269 --> 00:29:32,669
Goodbye, Gandalf.

357
00:29:35,269 --> 00:29:37,969
Goodbye, dear Bilbo.

358
00:29:45,870 --> 00:29:49,970
<i>The road goes ever on and on...</i>

359
00:29:52,670 --> 00:29:55,070
Until our next meeting.

360
00:30:22,471 --> 00:30:25,971
It's mine. My own.

361
00:30:26,271 --> 00:30:29,671
My precious.

362
00:30:29,971 --> 00:30:32,771
Riddles in the dark.

363
00:30:33,171 --> 00:30:34,571
Bilbo!

364
00:30:34,572 --> 00:30:36,172
Bilbo!

365
00:30:39,972 --> 00:30:42,872
My precious.

366
00:30:44,472 --> 00:30:46,572
Precious.

367
00:30:46,872 --> 00:30:49,272
He's gone, hasn't he?

368
00:30:52,272 --> 00:30:55,172
He talked for so long about leaving...

369
00:30:55,472 --> 00:30:58,072
...I didn't think he'd really do it.

370
00:31:02,673 --> 00:31:04,573
Gandalf?

371
00:31:12,873 --> 00:31:14,473
Bilbo's ring.

372
00:31:14,873 --> 00:31:17,173
He's gone to stay with the elves.

373
00:31:17,473 --> 00:31:20,373
He's left you Bag End.

374
00:31:24,173 --> 00:31:26,673
Along with all his possessions.

375
00:31:26,674 --> 00:31:29,674
The ring is yours now.

376
00:31:32,374 --> 00:31:35,773
- Put it somewhere out of sight.
- Where are you going?

377
00:31:35,774 --> 00:31:38,174
- There are some things that I must see to.
- What things?

378
00:31:38,474 --> 00:31:42,574
- Questions. Questions that need answering.
- You've only just arrived.

379
00:31:43,674 --> 00:31:46,174
I don't understand.

380
00:31:49,574 --> 00:31:50,575
Neither do I.

381
00:31:53,875 --> 00:31:56,174
Keep it secret.

382
00:31:56,175 --> 00:31:58,175
Keep it safe.

383
00:32:33,176 --> 00:32:35,276
Shire!

384
00:32:35,676 --> 00:32:37,694
Baggins!

385
00:32:38,536 --> 00:32:47,437
{\an8} [Adûnaic] ♫ <i>Nêbâbîtham Magânanê.</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ We renounce our Creator. ♫

386
00:33:27,278 --> 00:33:30,078
"The year 3434 of the second age.

387
00:33:30,378 --> 00:33:34,579
Here follows the account of Isildur,
High King of Gondor...

388
00:33:34,979 --> 00:33:38,579
...and the finding of the ring of power."

389
00:33:42,179 --> 00:33:43,979
"It has come to me.

390
00:33:44,279 --> 00:33:47,579
The one ring.
It shall be an heirloom of my kingdom.

391
00:33:47,879 --> 00:33:51,179
All those who follow in my bloodline
shall be bound to its fate...

392
00:33:51,579 --> 00:33:55,179
...for I will risk no hurt to the ring.

393
00:33:55,579 --> 00:33:57,979
It is precious to me...

394
00:33:58,980 --> 00:34:01,480
...though I buy it with great pain.

395
00:34:04,680 --> 00:34:08,680
The markings upon the band begin to fade.

396
00:34:09,180 --> 00:34:13,680
The writing, which at first was as clear
as red flame, has all but disappeared.

397
00:34:14,180 --> 00:34:17,980
A secret now that only fire can tell."

398
00:34:34,781 --> 00:34:37,680
Shire...

399
00:34:37,681 --> 00:34:39,781
...Baggins.

400
00:34:40,381 --> 00:34:44,281
There's no Bagginses around here.
They're all up in Hobbiton.

401
00:34:46,081 --> 00:34:47,481
That way.

402
00:34:51,282 --> 00:34:53,381
<i>"Hey ho to the dock I go</i>

403
00:34:53,382 --> 00:34:55,781
<i>To heal my heart and drown my woe</i>

404
00:34:55,782 --> 00:34:58,281
<i>Rain may fall and wind may blow</i>

405
00:34:58,282 --> 00:35:00,382
<i>But there still be...</i>

406
00:35:00,682 --> 00:35:01,982
<i>...many miles to go</i>

407
00:35:02,282 --> 00:35:04,182
<i>Sweet is the sound of the pouring rain</i>

408
00:35:04,482 --> 00:35:06,482
<i>And the stream that falls from hill to plain</i>

409
00:35:06,882 --> 00:35:08,582
<i>Better than rain or rippling brook</i>

410
00:35:08,882 --> 00:35:11,182
<i>Is a mug of beer inside this Took!"</i>

411
00:35:14,682 --> 00:35:17,383
There's been some strange folk crossing the Shire.

412
00:35:17,883 --> 00:35:21,583
Dwarves and others of a less than savory nature.

413
00:35:22,283 --> 00:35:23,683
War is brewing.

414
00:35:24,483 --> 00:35:27,083
The mountains are fair teeming with goblins.

415
00:35:27,383 --> 00:35:30,082
Far-off tales and children s stories, that's all that is.

416
00:35:30,083 --> 00:35:34,682
You're beginning to sound like that old
Bilbo Baggins. Cracked, he was.

417
00:35:34,683 --> 00:35:37,683
Young Mr. Frodo here, he's cracking.

418
00:35:38,083 --> 00:35:39,482
And proud of it.

419
00:35:39,483 --> 00:35:42,083
- Cheers, Gaffer.
- Aye. Cheers.

420
00:35:42,084 --> 00:35:46,084
Weel it's none of our concern what
goes on beyond our borders.

421
00:35:46,484 --> 00:35:50,484
Keep your nose out of trouble,
and no trouble'll come to you.

422
00:35:54,084 --> 00:35:56,183
- Good night, lads.
- Good night.

423
00:35:56,184 --> 00:36:00,784
Good night, sweet maiden of the golden ale.

424
00:36:01,084 --> 00:36:03,384
Mind who you're sweet-taking.

425
00:36:03,684 --> 00:36:07,985
Don't worry, Sam.
Rosie knows an idiot when she sees one.

426
00:36:09,185 --> 00:36:10,285
Does she?

427
00:36:10,985 --> 00:36:13,885
- Good night, Sam.
- Good night, Mr. Frodo.

428
00:36:38,786 --> 00:36:41,186
Is it secret? Is it safe?

429
00:36:50,186 --> 00:36:52,186
What are you doing?

430
00:37:04,887 --> 00:37:07,387
Hold out your hand, Frodo.

431
00:37:07,687 --> 00:37:08,787
It's quite cool.

432
00:37:12,287 --> 00:37:13,987
What can you see?

433
00:37:15,887 --> 00:37:18,187
Can you see anything?

434
00:37:21,087 --> 00:37:22,387
Nothing.

435
00:37:22,987 --> 00:37:24,888
There's nothing.

436
00:37:26,188 --> 00:37:27,588
Wait.

437
00:37:31,688 --> 00:37:33,888
There are markings.

438
00:37:35,488 --> 00:37:38,788
It's some form of Elvish.
I can't read it.

439
00:37:39,088 --> 00:37:41,488
There are few who can.

440
00:37:42,188 --> 00:37:46,788
The language is that of Mordor,
which I will not utter here.

441
00:37:47,688 --> 00:37:48,688
Mordor!

442
00:37:48,988 --> 00:37:50,889
In the common tongue, it says:

443
00:37:51,189 --> 00:37:54,589
"One ring to rule them all...

444
00:37:54,989 --> 00:37:57,189
...One ring to find them...

445
00:37:57,489 --> 00:37:59,589
...One ring to bring them all...

446
00:37:59,989 --> 00:38:02,889
...and in the darkness bind them."

447
00:38:04,689 --> 00:38:06,588
This is the One ring...

448
00:38:06,589 --> 00:38:11,889
...forged by the Dark Lord Sauron
in the fires of Mount Doom.

449
00:38:12,389 --> 00:38:16,190
Taken by Isildur from the hand of Sauron himself.

450
00:38:17,190 --> 00:38:19,590
Bilbo found it.

451
00:38:20,090 --> 00:38:21,990
- In Gollum's cave.
- Yes.

452
00:38:22,290 --> 00:38:26,690
For 60 years, the ring lay quiet in Bilbo's keeping...

453
00:38:27,090 --> 00:38:30,290
...prolonging his life, delaying old age.

454
00:38:31,090 --> 00:38:35,290
But no longer, Frodo.
Evil is stirring in Mordor.

455
00:38:35,690 --> 00:38:37,990
The ring has awoken.

456
00:38:38,290 --> 00:38:40,891
It's heard its master's call.

457
00:38:41,191 --> 00:38:44,891
But he was destroyed.
Sauron was destroyed.

458
00:38:50,791 --> 00:38:52,791
No, Frodo.

459
00:38:53,891 --> 00:38:57,091
The spirit of Sauron endured.

460
00:38:57,391 --> 00:39:02,491
His life force is bound to the ring,
and the ring survived.

461
00:39:02,991 --> 00:39:05,091
Sauron has returned.

462
00:39:06,191 --> 00:39:08,092
His orcs have multiplied.

463
00:39:08,492 --> 00:39:12,292
His fortress at Barad-dûr
is rebuilt in the land of Mordor.

464
00:39:12,592 --> 00:39:17,192
Sauron needs only this ring to cover
all the lands in a second darkness.

465
00:39:17,592 --> 00:39:19,592
He is seeking it.

466
00:39:19,892 --> 00:39:23,492
Seeking it - All his thought is bent on it.

467
00:39:23,992 --> 00:39:26,592
For the ring yearns above all else...

468
00:39:26,892 --> 00:39:30,192
...to return to the hand of its master.

469
00:39:30,592 --> 00:39:32,292
They are one...

470
00:39:32,293 --> 00:39:35,393
...the ring and the Dark Lord.

471
00:39:35,793 --> 00:39:36,793
Frodo...

472
00:39:37,293 --> 00:39:39,093
...he must never find it.

473
00:39:39,393 --> 00:39:40,393
All right.

474
00:39:40,793 --> 00:39:44,993
We put it away. We keep it hidden.
We never speak of it again.

475
00:39:45,393 --> 00:39:47,893
No one knows it's here, do they?

476
00:39:53,693 --> 00:39:54,793
Do they, Gandalf?

477
00:39:55,893 --> 00:39:59,194
There is one other who knew
that Bilbo had the ring.

478
00:40:00,594 --> 00:40:03,394
I looked everywhere for the creature Gollum.

479
00:40:03,794 --> 00:40:05,794
But the enemy found him first.

480
00:40:07,694 --> 00:40:10,094
I don't know how long they tortured him.

481
00:40:10,394 --> 00:40:14,694
But amidst the endless screams and
inane babble, they discerned two words:

482
00:40:14,994 --> 00:40:17,094
Shire!

483
00:40:17,394 --> 00:40:18,894
Baggins!

484
00:40:19,194 --> 00:40:20,993
Shire.

485
00:40:20,994 --> 00:40:23,895
Baggins.
But that would lead them here!

486
00:40:26,895 --> 00:40:27,895
Who goes there?

487
00:40:29,695 --> 00:40:30,895
Take it, Gandalf!

488
00:40:31,395 --> 00:40:32,394
- Take it!
- No, Frodo.

489
00:40:32,395 --> 00:40:34,795
- You must take it!
- You cannot offer me this ring!

490
00:40:35,095 --> 00:40:38,295
- I'm giving it to you!
- Don't tempt me, Frodo!

491
00:40:39,995 --> 00:40:42,095
I dare not take it.

492
00:40:42,495 --> 00:40:44,895
Not even to keep it safe.

493
00:40:46,095 --> 00:40:48,095
Understand, Frodo...

494
00:40:48,795 --> 00:40:52,296
...I would use this ring from a desire to do good.

495
00:40:57,796 --> 00:41:03,296
But through me, it would wield a power
too great and terrible to imagine.

496
00:41:04,196 --> 00:41:06,996
- But it cannot stay in the Shire!
- No.

497
00:41:08,996 --> 00:41:10,496
No, it can't.

498
00:41:15,897 --> 00:41:17,297
What must I do?

499
00:41:18,997 --> 00:41:22,297
- You must leave. And leave quickly.
- Where? Where do I go?

500
00:41:22,797 --> 00:41:25,897
Get out of the Shire.
Make for the village of Bree.

501
00:41:26,297 --> 00:41:27,297
Bree.

502
00:41:27,597 --> 00:41:30,197
- What about you?
- I'll be waiting for you...

503
00:41:30,497 --> 00:41:32,897
...at the inn of the Prancing Pony.

504
00:41:33,197 --> 00:41:36,797
- And the ring will be safe there?
- I don't know, Frodo.

505
00:41:37,097 --> 00:41:38,997
I don't have any answers.

506
00:41:40,598 --> 00:41:45,898
I must see the head of my order.
He is both wise and powerful. Trust me, Frodo.

507
00:41:46,298 --> 00:41:48,398
He'll know what to do.

508
00:41:49,098 --> 00:41:51,798
You'll have to leave the name
of Baggins behind you.

509
00:41:52,198 --> 00:41:54,598
That name is not safe outside the Shire.

510
00:41:55,298 --> 00:41:58,498
Travel only by day.
And stay off the road.

511
00:41:59,298 --> 00:42:02,398
I can cut across country easily enough.

512
00:42:04,998 --> 00:42:06,299
My dear Frodo.

513
00:42:06,599 --> 00:42:09,598
Hobbits really are amazing creatures.

514
00:42:09,599 --> 00:42:12,599
You can learn all that there is to
know about their ways in a month.

515
00:42:12,899 --> 00:42:15,199
And yet, after a hundred years...

516
00:42:15,499 --> 00:42:17,399
...they can still surprise you.

517
00:42:19,199 --> 00:42:20,499
Get down.

518
00:42:32,700 --> 00:42:36,000
Confound it all, Samwise Gamgee!
Have you been eavesdropping?

519
00:42:36,400 --> 00:42:37,800
I haven't been dropping no eaves. Honest.

520
00:42:38,100 --> 00:42:40,700
I was just cutting the grass under
the window there...If you follow me.

521
00:42:41,100 --> 00:42:43,400
A little late for trimming the verge, don't you think?

522
00:42:43,700 --> 00:42:46,499
- I heard raised voices.
- What did you hear? Speak!

523
00:42:46,500 --> 00:42:47,800
Nothing important.

524
00:42:48,400 --> 00:42:50,799
That is, I heard a good deal
about a ring, and a Dark Lord...

525
00:42:50,800 --> 00:42:52,499
...and something about the end of the world but...

526
00:42:52,500 --> 00:42:57,201
Please, Mr. Gandalf, sir, don't hurt me.
Don't turn me into anything unnatural.

527
00:42:58,201 --> 00:42:59,701
No?

528
00:43:01,001 --> 00:43:02,101
Perhaps not.

529
00:43:03,401 --> 00:43:06,701
I've thought of a better use for you.

530
00:43:08,501 --> 00:43:11,401
Come along, Samwise. Keep up.

531
00:43:13,101 --> 00:43:15,201
Be careful, both of you.

532
00:43:15,601 --> 00:43:18,201
The enemy has many spies in his service:

533
00:43:18,501 --> 00:43:21,301
Birds, beasts.

534
00:43:23,202 --> 00:43:25,002
Is it safe?

535
00:43:26,702 --> 00:43:28,002
Never put it on...

536
00:43:28,302 --> 00:43:31,601
...for the agents of the Dark Lord
will be drawn to its power.

537
00:43:31,602 --> 00:43:33,302
Always remember, Frodo...

538
00:43:33,902 --> 00:43:36,902
...the ring is trying to get back to its master.

539
00:43:37,502 --> 00:43:39,502
It wants to be found.

540
00:44:20,104 --> 00:44:22,204
This is it.

541
00:44:22,704 --> 00:44:24,704
This is what?

542
00:44:25,104 --> 00:44:27,104
If I take one more step...

543
00:44:27,704 --> 00:44:31,404
...it'll be the farthest away
from home I've ever been.

544
00:44:35,904 --> 00:44:37,304
Come on, Sam.

545
00:44:45,805 --> 00:44:47,605
Remember what Bilbo used to say:

546
00:44:48,205 --> 00:44:51,805
- "It's a dangerous business, Frodo."
- "Going out your door.

547
00:44:52,105 --> 00:44:56,405
You step onto the road,
and if you don't keep your feet...

548
00:44:56,705 --> 00:45:00,705
... there's no knowing where
you might be swept off to."

549
00:45:06,366 --> 00:45:14,805
{\an8} [Sindarin] ♫ <i>Rîn athar annún-aearath ...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ O Queen beyond the Western Seas... ♫

550
00:45:14,806 --> 00:45:15,765
Sam.

551
00:45:15,766 --> 00:45:20,105
{\an8} [Sindarin] ♫ <i>... calad ammen ...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ... light to us ... ♫

552
00:45:20,106 --> 00:45:20,966
Wood-elves.

553
00:45:20,967 --> 00:45:24,467
{\an8} [Sindarin] ♫ <i>... i reniar ...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ... who wander ... ♫

554
00:45:25,766 --> 00:45:33,767
{\an8} [Sindarin] ♫ <i>... mi 'aladhremmin Ennorath.</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ... amid the tree-woven lands of Middle-earth. ♫

555
00:45:34,907 --> 00:45:35,666
They're going to the harbor
beyond the White Towers.

556
00:45:35,667 --> 00:45:39,006
{\an8} [Sindarin] ♫ <i>A Elbereth Gilthoniel ...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ O Elbereth Star-kindler ... ♫

557
00:45:39,007 --> 00:45:40,607
To the Grey Havens.

558
00:45:41,307 --> 00:45:43,306
They're leaving Middle-earth.

559
00:45:43,307 --> 00:45:45,266
Never to return.

560
00:45:45,267 --> 00:45:48,606
{\an8} [Sindarin] ♫ <i>... i chin a thûl lín míriel.</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ... your eyes and breath shining like jewels. ♫

561
00:45:48,607 --> 00:45:50,607
I don't know why...

562
00:45:51,507 --> 00:45:53,807
...it makes me sad.

563
00:45:55,907 --> 00:46:00,308
Everywhere I lie there's a dirty
great root sticking into my back.

564
00:46:01,308 --> 00:46:03,007
Just shut your eyes...

565
00:46:03,008 --> 00:46:05,808
...and imagine you're back in your own bed...

566
00:46:06,208 --> 00:46:10,008
...with a soft mattress and a lovely feather pillow.

567
00:46:19,408 --> 00:46:22,007
It's not working, Mr. Frodo.

568
00:46:22,008 --> 00:46:25,009
I'm never going to be able to sleep out here.

569
00:46:27,409 --> 00:46:29,709
Me neither, Sam.

570
00:46:58,310 --> 00:47:01,310
Smoke rises from the Mountain of Doom.

571
00:47:01,610 --> 00:47:03,209
The hour grows late.

572
00:47:03,210 --> 00:47:06,810
And Gandalf the Grey rides to Isengard...

573
00:47:07,310 --> 00:47:09,610
...seeking my counsel.

574
00:47:09,910 --> 00:47:13,711
For that is why you have come, is it not?

575
00:47:14,011 --> 00:47:15,211
My old friend.

576
00:47:15,611 --> 00:47:17,111
Saruman.

577
00:47:22,011 --> 00:47:24,911
- You are sure of this?
- Beyond any doubt.

578
00:47:25,811 --> 00:47:28,011
So the ring of power has been found.

579
00:47:28,311 --> 00:47:31,311
All these long years, it was in the Shire.

580
00:47:31,711 --> 00:47:34,811
- Under my very nose.
- Yet you did not have the wit to see it.

581
00:47:35,511 --> 00:47:39,712
Your love of the halfling's leaf
has clearly slowed your mind.

582
00:47:40,612 --> 00:47:44,612
But we still have time.
Time enough to counter Sauron if we act quickly.

583
00:47:45,012 --> 00:47:46,412
Time?

584
00:47:47,512 --> 00:47:50,012
What time do you think we have?

585
00:47:50,512 --> 00:47:54,212
Sauron has regained much of his former strength.

586
00:47:54,612 --> 00:47:56,712
He cannot yet take physical form...

587
00:47:57,012 --> 00:47:59,612
...but his spirit has lost none of its potency.

588
00:48:00,312 --> 00:48:05,213
Concealed within his fortress,
the Lord of Mordor sees all.

589
00:48:06,013 --> 00:48:11,713
His gaze pierces cloud, shadow, earth and flesh.

590
00:48:13,513 --> 00:48:16,513
You know of what I speak, Gandalf.

591
00:48:17,513 --> 00:48:22,513
A great eye, lidless, wreathed in flame.

592
00:48:23,713 --> 00:48:25,413
The eye of Sauron.

593
00:48:25,713 --> 00:48:28,213
He is gathering all evil to him.

594
00:48:28,713 --> 00:48:30,414
Very soon, he'll have summoned an army...

595
00:48:30,714 --> 00:48:33,514
...great enough for an assault upon Middle-earth.

596
00:48:33,914 --> 00:48:36,214
You know this?

597
00:48:36,814 --> 00:48:38,314
How?

598
00:48:38,914 --> 00:48:40,514
I have seen it.

599
00:48:41,014 --> 00:48:44,114
A palantir is a dangerous tool, Saruman.

600
00:48:45,014 --> 00:48:46,414
Why?

601
00:48:46,914 --> 00:48:49,514
Why should we fear to use it?

602
00:48:52,314 --> 00:48:56,115
They are not all accounted for,
the lost seeing-stones.

603
00:48:56,415 --> 00:48:59,515
We do not know who else may be watching.

604
00:49:02,215 --> 00:49:04,914
The hour is later than you think.

605
00:49:04,915 --> 00:49:07,415
Sauron's forces are already moving.

606
00:49:09,715 --> 00:49:12,415
The Nine have left Minas Morgul.

607
00:49:12,815 --> 00:49:13,814
The Nine?

608
00:49:13,815 --> 00:49:16,915
They crossed the river Isen on Midsummer's Eve...

609
00:49:17,315 --> 00:49:19,915
...disguised as riders in black.

610
00:49:20,215 --> 00:49:24,016
- They've reached the Shire?
- They will find the ring.

611
00:49:25,716 --> 00:49:27,916
And kill the one who carries it.

612
00:49:28,416 --> 00:49:29,816
Frodo!

613
00:49:42,616 --> 00:49:46,816
You did not seriously think that a hobbit
could contend with the will of Sauron?

614
00:49:47,717 --> 00:49:50,417
There are none who can.

615
00:49:53,017 --> 00:49:55,617
Against the power of Mordor...

616
00:49:56,017 --> 00:49:58,517
...there can be no victory.

617
00:50:00,617 --> 00:50:03,617
We must join with him, Gandalf.

618
00:50:05,017 --> 00:50:07,217
We must join with Sauron.

619
00:50:10,017 --> 00:50:12,517
It would be wise, my friend.

620
00:50:13,218 --> 00:50:14,617
Tell me...

621
00:50:14,618 --> 00:50:16,318
...friend...

622
00:50:16,818 --> 00:50:21,218
...when did Saruman the Wise abandon reason for madness?

623
00:51:00,919 --> 00:51:02,519
I gave you the chance of...

624
00:51:03,719 --> 00:51:06,320
...aiding me willingly...

625
00:51:06,620 --> 00:51:10,620
...but you have elected the way of pain!

626
00:51:34,121 --> 00:51:35,521
Mr. Frodo?

627
00:51:36,221 --> 00:51:37,921
Frodo? Frodo!

628
00:51:39,421 --> 00:51:42,520
- I thought I'd lost you.
- What are you taking about?

629
00:51:42,521 --> 00:51:45,621
- It's just something Gandalf said.
- What did he say?

630
00:51:46,621 --> 00:51:50,321
"Don't you lose him, Samwise Gamgee."
And I don't mean to.

631
00:51:50,821 --> 00:51:54,321
Sam, we're still in the Shire.
What could possibly happen?

632
00:51:57,322 --> 00:51:58,322
Frodo.

633
00:51:58,622 --> 00:52:00,822
- Merry, it's Frodo Baggins.
- Hello, Frodo.

634
00:52:01,122 --> 00:52:02,422
Get off him.

635
00:52:03,022 --> 00:52:04,421
Come on, Frodo.

636
00:52:04,422 --> 00:52:06,422
What's the meaning of this?

637
00:52:06,922 --> 00:52:09,922
You've been into Farmer Maggot's crop!

638
00:52:11,222 --> 00:52:13,322
You get back here!

639
00:52:14,322 --> 00:52:15,622
Get out of my field!

640
00:52:15,922 --> 00:52:18,522
You'll know the devil if I catch up with you!

641
00:52:18,922 --> 00:52:21,723
I don't know why he's so upset.
It's only a couple of carrots.

642
00:52:22,023 --> 00:52:23,122
And some cabbages.

643
00:52:23,123 --> 00:52:26,222
And those three bags of potatoes
that we lifted last week.

644
00:52:26,223 --> 00:52:30,323
- And then the mushrooms the week before.
- Yes, Pippin. My point is...

645
00:52:30,723 --> 00:52:32,823
...he's clearly overreacting.

646
00:52:33,123 --> 00:52:34,523
Run!

647
00:52:48,024 --> 00:52:50,524
Oh, that was close.

648
00:52:51,724 --> 00:52:54,724
I think I've broken something.

649
00:52:55,824 --> 00:52:58,123
Trust a Brandybuck and a Took!

650
00:52:58,124 --> 00:53:01,824
What? That was just a detour.
A short cut.

651
00:53:02,224 --> 00:53:04,424
- Short cut to what?
- Mushrooms!

652
00:53:13,225 --> 00:53:14,625
That's mine.

653
00:53:17,425 --> 00:53:19,025
That's nice, Merry.

654
00:53:19,625 --> 00:53:21,624
Here's a nice one, Sam.

655
00:53:21,625 --> 00:53:24,225
I think we should get off the road.

656
00:53:33,625 --> 00:53:34,924
Get off the road!

657
00:53:34,925 --> 00:53:36,525
Quick!

658
00:53:49,326 --> 00:53:50,726
Be quiet!

659
00:54:57,129 --> 00:54:59,229
What was that?

660
00:55:32,030 --> 00:55:33,430
Anything?

661
00:55:34,230 --> 00:55:35,630
Nothing.

662
00:55:36,430 --> 00:55:38,630
What is going on?

663
00:55:39,230 --> 00:55:42,830
That Black Rider was looking for something.
Or someone.

664
00:55:44,330 --> 00:55:45,730
Frodo?

665
00:55:46,531 --> 00:55:47,531
Get down!

666
00:56:04,431 --> 00:56:06,631
I have to leave the Shire.

667
00:56:07,731 --> 00:56:10,030
Sam and I must get to Bree.

668
00:56:10,031 --> 00:56:11,631
Right.

669
00:56:13,032 --> 00:56:15,232
Bucklebury Ferry. Follow me.

670
00:56:23,632 --> 00:56:24,832
Run!

671
00:56:26,132 --> 00:56:28,032
This way! Follow me!

672
00:56:31,832 --> 00:56:32,732
Run!

673
00:56:46,033 --> 00:56:47,733
Get the rope, Sam!

674
00:56:50,433 --> 00:56:51,933
Frodo!

675
00:56:52,733 --> 00:56:54,033
Run, Frodo!

676
00:56:54,533 --> 00:56:55,532
Go!
- Hurry!

677
00:56:55,533 --> 00:56:58,233
Frodo, come on!

678
00:56:59,333 --> 00:57:01,333
- Come on! Faster!
- Jump!

679
00:57:16,334 --> 00:57:20,334
- How far to the nearest crossing?
- The Brandywine Bridge. 20 miles.

680
00:57:35,135 --> 00:57:36,635
Come on.

681
00:57:47,835 --> 00:57:51,135
- What do you want?
- We're heading for the Prancing Pony.

682
00:57:54,736 --> 00:57:57,535
Hobbits. Four hobbits!

683
00:57:57,536 --> 00:58:01,536
What's more, out of the Shire by your talk.
What business brings you to Bree?

684
00:58:02,236 --> 00:58:05,236
We wish to stay at the inn.
Our business is our own.

685
00:58:06,436 --> 00:58:08,836
All right young sir, I meant no offense.

686
00:58:09,136 --> 00:58:11,536
It's my job to ask questions after nightfall.

687
00:58:11,936 --> 00:58:14,735
There's talk of strange folk abroad.

688
00:58:14,736 --> 00:58:17,036
Can't be too careful.

689
00:58:36,837 --> 00:58:40,137
Out of the way!
Watch where you're walking.

690
00:59:04,338 --> 00:59:05,838
Excuse me.

691
00:59:06,938 --> 00:59:09,638
Good evening, little masters.
What can I do for you?

692
00:59:09,938 --> 00:59:15,739
If you're looking for accommodation, we got
some nice cozy hobbit-sized rooms available.

693
00:59:16,239 --> 00:59:20,739
Always proud to cater to little folk, Mister...?

694
00:59:21,939 --> 00:59:23,939
Underhill. My name's Underhill.

695
00:59:25,339 --> 00:59:27,739
- Underhill, yeah.
- We're friends of Gandalf the Grey.

696
00:59:28,039 --> 00:59:31,039
- Can you tell him we've arrived?
- Gandalf?

697
00:59:31,539 --> 00:59:33,239
Gandalf.

698
00:59:34,139 --> 00:59:35,739
Oh, yes...

699
00:59:36,039 --> 00:59:38,040
...I remember. Elderly chap.

700
00:59:38,440 --> 00:59:41,340
Big grey beard, pointy hat.

701
00:59:41,740 --> 00:59:43,540
Not seen him for six months.

702
00:59:50,440 --> 00:59:51,740
What do we do now?

703
00:59:58,940 --> 01:00:00,139
Sam...

704
01:00:00,140 --> 01:00:02,140
...he'll be here. He'll come.

705
01:00:05,041 --> 01:00:07,041
Get out of my way!

706
01:00:09,541 --> 01:00:11,140
What's that?

707
01:00:11,141 --> 01:00:13,741
This, my friend, is a pint.

708
01:00:14,141 --> 01:00:15,641
It comes in pints?

709
01:00:16,041 --> 01:00:19,541
- I'm getting one.
- You got a whole half already!

710
01:00:26,041 --> 01:00:29,742
That fellow's done nothing but
stare at you since we arrived.

711
01:00:33,542 --> 01:00:34,942
Excuse me.

712
01:00:36,842 --> 01:00:39,642
That man in the corner. Who is he?

713
01:00:41,042 --> 01:00:45,242
He's one of them Rangers. They're dangerous
folk they are, wandering the wilds.

714
01:00:45,542 --> 01:00:49,942
What his right name is, I've never heard,
but 'round here he's known as Strider.

715
01:00:52,442 --> 01:00:53,642
Strider.

716
01:01:06,743 --> 01:01:09,843
<i>Baggins...</i>

717
01:01:13,043 --> 01:01:15,943
<i>Baggins...</i>

718
01:01:20,344 --> 01:01:22,644
<i>Baggins...</i>

719
01:01:23,944 --> 01:01:26,344
<i>Baggins...</i>

720
01:01:27,044 --> 01:01:29,944
<i>Baggins...
Baggins? Sure, I know a Baggins.</i>

721
01:01:30,644 --> 01:01:33,243
He's over there. Frodo Baggins.

722
01:01:33,244 --> 01:01:36,543
He's my second cousin,
once removed on his mother's side...

723
01:01:36,544 --> 01:01:38,844
...and my third cousin, twice removed....

724
01:01:43,444 --> 01:01:45,144
- Pippin!
- Steady on, Frodo.

725
01:02:14,746 --> 01:02:17,146
<i>You cannot hide.</i>

726
01:02:20,146 --> 01:02:23,146
<i>I see you.</i>

727
01:02:25,046 --> 01:02:27,645
<i>There is no life...</i>

728
01:02:27,646 --> 01:02:29,946
<i>...in the void.</i>

729
01:02:30,246 --> 01:02:31,646
<i>Only...</i>

730
01:02:32,646 --> 01:02:34,146
<i>...death.</i>

731
01:02:40,147 --> 01:02:44,847
You draw far too much attention
to yourself, "Mr. Underhill."

732
01:02:49,747 --> 01:02:50,647
What do you want?

733
01:02:50,947 --> 01:02:52,947
A little more caution from you.
That is no trinket you carry.

734
01:02:53,447 --> 01:02:56,347
- I carry nothing.
- Indeed.

735
01:02:56,747 --> 01:02:59,147
I can avoid being seen if I wish...

736
01:02:59,447 --> 01:03:02,948
...but to disappear entirely, that is a rare gift.

737
01:03:03,648 --> 01:03:06,148
- Who are you?
- Are you frightened?

738
01:03:07,548 --> 01:03:08,447
Yes.

739
01:03:08,448 --> 01:03:12,448
Not nearly frightened enough.
I know what hunts you.

740
01:03:16,548 --> 01:03:18,948
Let him go!
Or I'll have you, Longshanks.

741
01:03:20,848 --> 01:03:24,748
You have a stout heart, little hobbit.
But that will not save you.

742
01:03:25,148 --> 01:03:27,949
You can no longer wait for the wizard, Frodo.

743
01:03:28,249 --> 01:03:29,249
They're coming.

744
01:03:34,389 --> 01:03:38,600
{\an8} [Adûnaic] ♫ <i>Bârî'n Katha-râd...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ The Lords of the Eternal life... ♫

745
01:03:39,659 --> 01:03:45,059
{\an8} [Adûnaic] ♫ <i>...îdô Nidir...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ...now the Nine... ♫

746
01:03:45,383 --> 01:03:48,883
{\an8} [Adûnaic] ♫ <i>...nênâ-kham, nêpâm...</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ...we come, we grasp... ♫

747
01:03:50,907 --> 01:03:54,908
{\an8} [Adûnaic] ♫ <i>...abarat aglar.</i> ♫
{\an8} [English] ♫ ...power and glory. ♫

748
01:04:52,952 --> 01:04:54,352
What are they?

749
01:04:56,552 --> 01:04:58,652
They were once men.

750
01:04:58,952 --> 01:05:01,052
Great kings of men.

751
01:05:01,652 --> 01:05:04,652
Then Sauron the Deceiver gave to them
nine rings of power.

752
01:05:05,452 --> 01:05:08,452
Blinded by their greed,
they took them without question.

753
01:05:08,752 --> 01:05:11,953
One by one, falling into darkness.

754
01:05:12,253 --> 01:05:14,653
Now they are slaves to his will.

755
01:05:17,153 --> 01:05:18,752
They are the Nazgûl.

756
01:05:18,753 --> 01:05:21,553
Ringwraiths. Neither living nor dead.

757
01:05:22,553 --> 01:05:23,952
At all times they feel...

758
01:05:23,953 --> 01:05:25,953
... the presence of the ring...

759
01:05:26,253 --> 01:05:30,553
...drawn to the power of the One.
They will never stop hunting you.

760
01:05:40,754 --> 01:05:43,554
- Where are you taking us?
- Into the wild.

761
01:05:51,954 --> 01:05:55,754
How can we know this Strider
is a friend of Gandalf?

762
01:05:56,154 --> 01:05:58,954
I think a servant of the enemy would look fairer...

763
01:05:59,354 --> 01:06:03,155
...and feel fouler.
- He's foul enough.

764
01:06:03,855 --> 01:06:06,655
We have no choice but to trust him.

765
01:06:06,955 --> 01:06:10,155
- But where is he leading us?
- To Rivendell, Master Gamgee.

766
01:06:12,655 --> 01:06:15,855
- To the house of Elrond.
- Did you hear that? Rivendell.

767
01:06:16,555 --> 01:06:19,255
We're going to see the elves.

768
01:06:40,956 --> 01:06:45,056
- Gentlemen, we do not stop till nightfall.
- What about breakfast?

769
01:06:45,356 --> 01:06:48,055
- You've already had it.
- We've had one, yes.

770
01:06:48,056 --> 01:06:50,456
What about second breakfast?

771
01:06:53,857 --> 01:06:56,857
Don't think he knows about second breakfast, Pip.

772
01:06:57,357 --> 01:07:02,357
What about elevenses? Luncheon?
Afternoon tea? Dinner? Supper?

773
01:07:02,757 --> 01:07:06,757
- He knows about them, doesn't he?
- I wouldn't count on it.

774
01:07:12,357 --> 01:07:13,957
Pippin!

775
01:07:30,458 --> 01:07:33,758
What do they eat when they can't get Hobbit?

